Libraries

This week we will be using tidyverse and ggplot2.

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

Dataset: Starwars

Exercise 1: Modify the following plot to change the color of all points to "pink".

ggplot(
  starwars,
  aes(x = height, y = mass, color = gender, size = birth_year)
) +
  geom_point(color = "pink")

Exercise 2: Add labels for title, x and y axes, and size of points.

library(viridis)
ggplot(
  starwars,
  aes(x = height, y = mass, color = gender, size = birth_year)
) +
  geom_point(color = "#30509C") +
  labs(
    title = "Mass by Height x Gender x Birth Year",
    x = "Height",
    y = "Mass",
    size = "Birth Year"
  )

Exercise 3: Pick a single categorical variable from the data set and make a bar plot of its distribution.

ggplot(starwars, aes(homeworld, fill = homeworld)) +
  geom_bar() +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "Homeworld", y = "Frequency")

Exercise 4: Pick a single numerical variable and make a histogram of it.

(This time no starter code is provided, youre on your own!)

ggplot(starwars, aes(mass)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "blue", fill = "purple") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Mass", y = "Frequency")

Exercise 5: Pick a numerical variable and a categorical variable and make a visualisation (you pick the type!) to visualise the relationship between the two variables. Along with your code and output, provide an interpretation of the visualisation.

For this one, you want to plot the mean on the y-axis, NOT the frequency.

ggplot(starwars %>% filter(!is.na(gender)), aes(x = gender, y = mass, fill = gender)) +
  stat_summary(geom = "bar", fun = "mean") +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Gender Trait", y = "Mean Mass (g)")

Exercise 6: Pick two categorical variables and make a visualisation to visualise the relationship between the two variables. Along with your code and output, provide an interpretation of the visualisation.

ggplot(starwars %>% filter(!is.na(gender)) %>% filter(!is.na(hair_color)), aes(hair_color, fill = gender)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "Hair Color", y = "Frequency", fill = "Gender Trait")
